<task id="011" project="email-communication-solution-r3">
  <metadata>
    <title>Build EmailComposer engine — state machine + imperative handle (5 modes × 3 mounts)</title>
    <phase>Wave 1 — Engine + Wrappers + Sub-Components</phase>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-hours>10</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>010</dependencies>
    <blocks>012, 013, 014, 015, 016, 017, 018, 019, 020, 021, 022, 023, 024, 025, 026, 027</blocks>
    <tags>react, frontend, fluent-ui, state-machine, communication</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Engine implementation — the load-bearing centerpiece of the entire project; modifies `.tsx`/`.ts`; architecture-level decisions (state machine shape, imperative handle contract, mount-variant layout); blocks 16 downstream tasks; ADR-021 (Fluent v9), ADR-028 (auth decoupling), NFR-01 (React 18), NFR-02 (no `@spaarke/auth` import), NFR-03 (mount variants) all bind here. FULL is non-negotiable.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Engine is the foundation for all sub-components, wrappers, and modes — every Wave 1 task after this reads `EmailComposer.tsx` / `EmailComposer.types.ts` / `EmailComposer.reducer.ts`. Cannot parallelize.</parallel-reason>
    <fr-refs>FR-01, FR-08, FR-09</fr-refs>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Build the canonical `<EmailComposer />` engine in `src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/EmailComposer/EmailComposer.tsx`. This is THE engine — the entire project hangs on getting this right.

    Engine requirements (FR-01):
    - 5 modes: `compose`, `view`, `reply`, `forward`, `draft`
    - 3 mounts: `inline`, `dialog`, `page`
    - 15 combinations of mode × mount, all must render and behave correctly
    - Internal state via `useReducer` (NOT scattered `useState`); state machine shape captured in `EmailComposer.reducer.ts`
    - Imperative handle via `useImperativeHandle` exposing `validate()`, `send()`, `saveDraft()`, `getState()` — wizard hosts call these via `composerRef`
    - React 18 only (NFR-01) — free use of `useId`, `useTransition`, etc.

    Critical constraints:
    - **No direct `@spaarke/auth` import** (NFR-02). Network calls use an `authenticatedFetch: (input, init) => Promise<Response>` prop injected by the host. Engine remains auth-library-agnostic.
    - **Fluent UI v9 only** (ADR-021). Use `@fluentui/react-components` primitives + design tokens; dark mode passes through automatically via Fluent theme provider.
    - **Mount variants** (NFR-03):
      - `page`: full-width form layout; section dividers; prominent bottom-right action bar; page header showing entity context
      - `dialog`: bounded width ~600px; compressed spacing; dialog header + footer action bar
      - `inline`: fills wizard step container; NO internal header or action bar (wizard frame owns navigation)
    - **Sub-components are NOT yet built** — engine should render placeholder slots that downstream tasks (012-019) fill in. Engine should compile and render an empty skeleton at end of this task.
    - **Validation contract** (FR-08): `validate(): IValidationResult[]` with `{ field, code, message }` — canonical codes implemented in task 020; engine returns `[]` as a stub until 020 lands.
    - **Error contract** (FR-09): `send()` throws `SendCommunicationError` on non-2xx — the class itself was added in Wave 0 task 005; engine imports it from `communicationApi.ts`.

    Files to create in this task:
    - `EmailComposer.tsx` (engine component, `forwardRef` + `useImperativeHandle`)
    - `EmailComposer.types.ts` (`IEmailComposerProps`, `IEmailComposerHandle`, `EmailComposerState`, `EmailComposerAction`, `EmailComposerMode`, `EmailComposerMount`, `IComposerAssociation`, `IComposerAttachmentSource`)
    - `EmailComposer.reducer.ts` (`emailComposerReducer`, `initialState(props)`)
    - Update `EmailComposer/index.ts` — uncomment the `EmailComposer` export
    - Uncomment the EmailComposer barrel line in `src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/index.ts`

    Engine intentionally compiles to a minimal-but-correct skeleton — sub-components in `subcomponents/` slot in via tasks 012-019; mode-specific logic via 024-027.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior React + TypeScript developer fluent in Fluent UI v9 + state-machine modeling. Comfortable with `useReducer`, `forwardRef`, `useImperativeHandle`, and the imperative-handle-from-wizard-host pattern already used elsewhere in the shared lib (e.g., `CreateRecordWizard` patterns).
  </role>

  <goal>
    `EmailComposer.tsx` compiles, lint-clean, renders an empty-but-correct skeleton for all 15 mode × mount combinations. Imperative handle methods (`validate()`, `send()`, `saveDraft()`, `getState()`) exist as stubs that downstream tasks fully wire. Mount-variant layout (NFR-03) visible: `page` = full-width form chrome, `dialog` = ~600px compact, `inline` = no chrome. Shared lib `npm run build` + `npm run lint` clean. Barrel exports updated.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      The engine is what replaces 6 ad-hoc client-side email implementations (Owner Clarifications + design.md §2). It MUST be the only React component that knows about email-send mechanics; wrappers (021-023) are thin (~30-60 LOC each) and only lock the `mount` prop.

      Imperative handle pattern: wizard hosts hold a `composerRef = useRef<IEmailComposerHandle>()` and call `composerRef.current.send()` on Finish, `composerRef.current.validate()` on step-change. This pattern is mirrored from the existing `CreateRecordWizard` pattern.

      Wave 0 task 005 already added `SendCommunicationError` to `communicationApi.ts` (per CLAUDE.md Empirical Finding #2). Engine imports from there.

      Sub-components (012-019) render INSIDE the engine — engine should reserve clear slot/region elements (e.g., a `<HeaderSlot />`, `<RecipientsSlot />`, `<BodySlot />`, `<AttachmentsSlot />`, `<ActionsSlot />`) that the downstream tasks fill in.

      Per NFR-02, the engine must NOT `import` from `@spaarke/auth`. Instead the host injects `authenticatedFetch` via props. The communicationApi.ts wrapper already takes `authenticatedFetch` as a parameter — engine forwards from its prop.
    </background>
